{
  "texts": [
    "Sequence-based methods (Fig. 3a, c, Box 2) appeal as well to deep CNNs 116, 117, 128, 134, 135, 137, 138, 140, 141, 144, 145, while in general spanning a variety of ML architectures, from decision trees and random forests 129, 150, 151 to networks based on the attention mechanism 122, 134, 139, 140 (Box 3).",
    "Most recently, sequence-based methods have benefitted from the breakthroughs in ML for natural language processing, with several methods for epitopeparatope interactions and paratope prediction directly using language model ML architectures 116, 121, [123] [124] [125] [126] 130, 136, 137, 146 (Box 3).",
    "These architectures capture potentially long-range dependencies between residues along the sequence, resulting in representations of each protein site capable of incorporating the effect of the physico-chemical context 152, 153.",
    "A recent public benchmark of sequence-based methods to predict TCR-epitope specificity has flagged up a few important trends 115.",
    "Firstly, data set the performance to a larger extent than the particular model architecture."
  ]
}